{
  "response_text": "The mean household risk attitude initiates at a near-neutral level of 0.0074 and increases rapidly during the first third of the simulation, reaching a maximum value of 0.3814 by year 33. This early phase is characterized by statistically significant upward trends, with the strongest positive momentum occurring between years 11 and 21, where the slope indicates a consistent annual increase. The ascent reflects the initial adaptation period as farmers with diverse learning strategies begin processing environmental feedback and adjusting their risk dispositions in response to pasture conditions.\n\nFollowing the peak at year 33, the aggregate risk attitude enters a prolonged decline lasting approximately three decades. By year 46, values have fallen to 0.2691, and the downward trajectory continues through year 65, where the metric approaches 0.1913. This middle period exhibits statistically significant decreasing trends across consecutive analysis windows, with the rate of decline being steepest immediately after the peak (years 33-43) at a slope of -0.010 per year. The decrease suggests a collective recalibration toward more conservative risk postures as farmers accumulate experience with the variable rainfall conditions (mean 200, standard deviation 100) and vegetation dynamics.\n\nAfter year 65, the system stabilizes with the mean risk attitude fluctuating around 0.1911 through year 100, showing no statistically significant directional trends in the final decades. The oscillation analysis reveals a dominant periodicity of approximately 49 years, with inflection points at years 46, 51, and subsequent intervals indicating the transition from active adjustment to equilibrium.\n\nWhile the aggregate trajectory follows this rise-plateau-fall pattern, individual simulation runs demonstrate substantial path-dependent divergence. From approximately year 20 onward, distinct farming populations separate into divergent risk cultures: some communities evolve highly risk-seeking dispositions stabilizing near 0.8, others maintain moderate risk tolerance between 0.2 and 0.6, and some develop strongly risk-averse postures declining to -0.4. This heterogeneity suggests that despite homogeneous initial conditions and identical learning strategy distributions, stochastic variation in early environmental feedback and neighbor interactions leads to the emergence of divergent collective risk attitudes. The dispersion becomes permanent by mid-simulation, indicating that single-loop learning within fixed behavioral types produces persistent divergence in how farming communities interpret and respond to uncertainty in stocking decisions."
}

